CAPE TOWN - The case against five men accused of murdering a Cape Town e-hailing driver has been postponed to next week. They were arrested in connection with the killing of 31-year-old Abongile Mafalala. Mafalala died after the vehicle he was travelling in came under attack - and was set alight in Parkwood last week. #AbongileMafalala The case against five men arrested in connection with the killing of Cape Town e-hailing driver, Abongile Mafalala, has been postponed until next Monday. Dunoon residents, where Abongile lived, demonstrated outside the Wynberg Magistrates Court. KB pic.twitter.com/3pgpQUTTaS  Supporters wearing t-shirts with the slogan "Justice for Abongile" demonstrated outside the Wynberg Magistrates Court. Five men, aged between 20 and 36, appeared in court on Monday on schedule six charges of murder, aggravated robbery and malicious damage to property. #AbongileMafala The accused face charges of Murder, Aggravated Robbery and Malicious damage to property. KB pic.twitter.com/95XRSTCPZE  Organiser of the demonstration, Thobeka Pikini, wants justice for her friend and former colleague. "We come to support Abongile's family. We did not come to fight or protest anything we just want justice and to show support to this family". Detectives said a sixth accused has turned State witness and the matter would be back in court next Monday.